# PR Creation And Template Policy

## Auto-merge
- Create PRs with auto-merge enabled when possible.
- If auto-merge is not enabled on creation, enable it immediately after creation.
- Treat PR creation as incomplete until auto-merge is enabled.

## Template
- Use `.github/pull_request_template.md` for every PR description.
- Fill required sections with project-specific details.
- Remove placeholders and irrelevant optional notes.
- Keep template content focused on PR context (`summary`, `scope`, `validation`, `risks`), not manual operator steps.
- Never mention auto-merge in the PR template body or checklist.
- Handle auto-merge as an execution step after PR creation, outside the template text.
- In `Summary`, explain how the change supports the current project purpose.
- In `Risks`, acknowledge early-stage/small-project constraints (limited surface area, fast iteration, and pragmatic scope) and how this PR keeps risk controlled.
- Assume this project is built by one engineer with AI assistance; prefer concise, high-signal PR descriptions over heavyweight process text.
- Keep validation proportional to change risk: a small set of meaningful checks is enough when it demonstrates confidence.

## Branch Scope Accuracy
- Before creating a PR, fetch and compare the full branch against remote main (`git fetch origin main` and `git diff origin/main...HEAD`).
- Ensure the PR title and description reflect all changes present in that full branch diff, not only the latest commit or staged/uncommitted files.
- If the branch contains unrelated work, split it first or explicitly call out the extra scope in the PR text.
